The Interactive Biodiversity Adventure

A static but immersive exhibit that brings four extreme ecosystems together in one model, designed for clear understanding and strong visual impact.

Ocean Rainforest Antarctic Desert Biodiversity
Expo exhibit preview

One model, four ecosystems. Scan the QR code to explore how life adapts in each biome while viewing the physical exhibit.

About the project

The exhibit is built on a simple idea. Biodiversity looks different in each part of the world because every ecosystem sets its own rules of survival.

By placing the deep Ocean, lush Rainforest, frozen Antarctic, and harsh Desert side by side, the model shows how life adapts, transforms, and still flourishes under extreme conditions. Diversity is shaped by climate, landforms, and ecological relationships, not by chance.

Tap an ecosystem to explore it
Ocean ecosystem
Deep water biodiversity

The ocean section uses layered waves and structure to show depth, pressure, and motion. Species placement follows real marine zones, from surface life to deeper organisms.

It explains how life adjusts to

  • Low light conditions
  • High pressure at deeper levels
  • Constant water movement and currents
Realistic waves Depth zones Marine food chains
Ocean model detail
Rainforest ecosystem
Dense green hotspot

The rainforest section uses stacked foliage and canopy layers to show how life fills every level, from forest floor to treetops.

It highlights

  • High species richness and variety
  • Complex, interlinked food webs
  • Strong links between climate, water, and life
Layered canopy Biodiversity hotspot Warm, wet climate
Rainforest model detail
Antarctic ecosystem
Frozen extremes

The Antarctic section uses crisp ice plates and stark colours to show a low temperature, low light world.

It focuses on

  • Adaptations to extreme cold
  • Strong seasonal changes in light
  • Fewer but highly specialised species
Ice textures Polar species Extreme climate
Antarctic model detail
Desert ecosystem
Heat and scarcity

The desert section uses dune like surfaces and sparse vegetation to show survival with limited water and strong heat.

It illustrates

  • Water storage and conservation strategies
  • Nocturnal activity to avoid daytime heat
  • Ways plants and animals manage light and temperature
Dune textures Drought adaptations Harsh climate
